<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-12231">
<article id="comment-12231" class="comment">
<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/816e40c4145bef96d757c28b3bc55f8a?s=44&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/816e40c4145bef96d757c28b3bc55f8a?s=88&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' loading='lazy' decoding='async' /><cite><b class="fn">Ed.</b> </cite><a href="https://allaboutcats.com/ginger-cats#comment-12231"><time datetime="2018-07-01T23:07:39+00:00">Jul 1, 2018 at 11:07 pm</time></a> </header>
<section class="comment-content comment">
<p>My little lad&#8230;well he is nearly 2 and half now is a very cheeky Ginger. He knows the word sit, fridge, ham&#8230;he is a mega ham fiend&#8230;he also knows the word no, and he hates it he gets in a right mood. He tolerates a bath&#8230;just and loves kisses, he also likes to play and can be hard at times with his leaping and nipping-many a bruise on my upper arms. </p>
<p>He came to us as a 4 month old, a stray, he bounded up the drive to me and my wife and decided to follow us into the house and he just stayed&#8230;we are not cat people but he melted our hearts on the spot.</p>
<p>He is spoilt rotten with with toys that he never plays with&#8230;a £50 scratching tree with house that he never bothered with&#8230;but, that is the way it goes. He does love chasing you and chasing after a ball. </p>
<p>They say cats do not really respond to a name&#8230;well, Tigs certainly does, he comes when called or whistled. </p>
<p>We couldn&#8217;t be without him now, our lovely Ginger boy.</p>
</section>
