<li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="li-comment-35875">
<article id="comment-35875" class="comment">
<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/a2d863fc2220713bcbb30aef5f359cf9?s=44&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/a2d863fc2220713bcbb30aef5f359cf9?s=88&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' loading='lazy' decoding='async' /><cite><b class="fn">Sam</b> </cite><a href="https://allaboutcats.com/ginger-cats#comment-35875"><time datetime="2019-11-19T23:23:34+00:00">Nov 19, 2019 at 11:23 pm</time></a> </header>
<section class="comment-content comment">
<p>Usually, a spritz of water at a cat is a good deterrent. Although some cats like water and this is not effective.<br />
Some cats are only doing &#8216;love bites&#8217; and don&#8217;t actually do a real bite. It can be alarming if you are not used to it.<br />
I used to have an orange manx who would nip at our ankles if he wanted something. Usually it was food, sometimes water, going outside, or affection.<br />
Jackson Galaxy is a cat behavior expert and gives pretty good advice, you should google him, he gives out tips.</p>
</section>
