<li class="comment byuser comment-author-mcrustawildernesscat-com even depth-2" id="li-comment-41257">
<article id="comment-41257" class="comment">
<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
<img alt='small mallory photo' src='https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/cropped-Small-pfp-44x44.jpg' srcset='https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/cropped-Small-pfp-88x88.jpg 2x' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' loading='lazy' decoding='async' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='https://www.wildernesscat.com/' rel='external nofollow ugc' class='url'>Mallory Crusta</a></b> </cite><a href="https://allaboutcats.com/ginger-cats#comment-41257"><time datetime="2020-07-29T01:26:34+00:00">Jul 29, 2020 at 1:26 am</time></a> </header>
<section class="comment-content comment">
<p>Hey there, it sounds like your Tiger is a pretty big kitty! As long as his body condition is within the healthy range, I would assume that his size is normal and perfectly healthy. You can learn more about feline body condition scoring here: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/feline-obesity" rel="nofollow ugc">https://allaboutcats.com/feline-obesity</a></p>
</section>
